[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] View patterns generalize predicate patterns, allowing further matching on the result of the function rather than simply expecting a Boolean value.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Some pattern languages allow direct comparison of portions of the scrutinee with previously-computed (or constant) data structures.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] In Erlang, mention of any variable already in scope in a pattern causes it to act as a constraint in this way (instead of as a binding).
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Some languages allow macros in pattern context to allow abstraction over patterns.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The simplest pattern in pattern matching is an explicit value or a variable.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Now, whenever f is given 0 as argument the pattern matches and the function returns 1.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] With any other argument, the matching and thus the function fail.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Here, the first `n` is a single variable pattern, which will match absolutely any argument and bind it to name n to be used in the rest of the definition.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] In Haskell (unlike at least Hope), patterns are tried in order so the first definition still applies in the very specific case of the input being 0, while for any other argument the function returns `n * f (n-1)` with n being the argument.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The wildcard pattern (often written as `_`) is also simple: like a variable name, it matches any value, but does not bind the value to any name.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Algorithms for matching wildcards in simple string-matching situations have been developed in a number of recursive and non-recursive varieties.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] More complex patterns can be built from the primitive ones of the previous section, usually in the same way as values are built by combining other values.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The difference then is that with variable and wildcard parts, a pattern does not build into a single value, but matches a group of values that are the combination of the concrete elements and the elements that are allowed to vary within the structure of the pattern.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] A tree pattern describes a part of a tree by starting with a node and specifying some branches and nodes and leaving some unspecified with a variable or wildcard pattern.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] It may help to think of the abstract syntax tree of a programming language and algebraic data types.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] In Haskell, the following line defines an algebraic data type `Color` that has a single data constructor `ColorConstructor` that wraps an integer and a string.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The constructor is a node in a tree and the integer and string are leaves in branches.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] When we want to write functions to make `Color` an abstract data type, we wish to write functions to interface with the data type, and thus we want to extract some data from the data type, for example, just the string or just the integer part of `Color`.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] If we pass a variable that is of type Color, how can we get the data out of this variable?
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The creations of these functions can be automated by Haskell's data record syntax.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] This OCaml example which defines a red–black tree and a function to re-balance it after element insertion shows how to match on a more complex structure generated by a recursive data type.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The compiler verifies at compile-time that the list of cases is exhaustive and none are redundant.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Pattern matching can be used to filter data of a certain structure.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, the only structure that exists is the tree, which is populated by symbols.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] In the traditional, more suitable syntax, the symbols are written as they are and the levels of the tree are represented using `[]`, so that for instance `a[b,c]` is a tree with a as the parent, and b and c as the children.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] A pattern in Mathematica involves putting "_" at positions in that tree.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] will match elements such as A[1], A[2], or more generally A[*x*] where *x* is any entity.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] In this case, `A` is the concrete element, while `_` denotes the piece of tree that can be varied.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] A symbol prepended to `_` binds the match to that variable name while a symbol appended to `_` restricts the matches to nodes of that symbol.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Note that even blanks themselves are internally represented as `Blank[]` for `_` and `Blank[x]` for `_x`.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Pattern matching applies to the *structure* of expressions.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] because only these elements will match the pattern `a[b[_],_]` above.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, it is also possible to extract structures as they are created in the course of computation, regardless of how or where they appear.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The function `Trace` can be used to monitor a computation, and return the elements that arise which match a pattern.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Then, we can ask the question: Given fib[3], what is the sequence of recursive Fibonacci calls?
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] In symbolic programming languages, it is easy to have patterns as arguments to functions or as elements of data structures.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] A consequence of this is the ability to use patterns to declaratively make statements about pieces of data and to flexibly instruct functions how to operate.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] For instance, the Mathematica function `Compile` can be used to make more efficient versions of the code.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The Curry–Howard correspondence between proofs and programs relates ML-style pattern matching to case analysis and proof by exhaustion.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] By far the most common form of pattern matching involves strings of characters.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] In many programming languages, a particular syntax of strings is used to represent regular expressions, which are patterns describing string characters.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] However, it is possible to perform some string pattern matching within the same framework that has been discussed throughout this article.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, strings are represented as trees of root StringExpression and all the characters in order as children of the root.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Thus, to match "any amount of trailing characters", a new wildcard ___ is needed in contrast to _ that would match only a single character.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] In Haskell and functional programming languages in general, strings are represented as functional lists of characters.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] A functional list is defined as an empty list, or an element constructed on an existing list.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The structure for a list with some elements is thus `element:list`.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] When pattern matching, we assert that a certain piece of data is equal to a certain pattern.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] We assert that the first element of `head`'s argument is called element, and the function returns this.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] We know that this is the first element because of the way lists are defined, a single element constructed onto a list.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The empty list would not match the pattern at all, as an empty list does not have a head (the first element that is constructed).
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] will match a string that has two characters and begins with "a".
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Symbolic entities can be introduced to represent many different classes of relevant features of a string.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] will match a string that consists of a letter first, and then a number.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The main advantage of symbolic string manipulation is that it can be completely integrated with the rest of the programming language, rather than being a separate, special purpose subunit.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] The entire power of the language can be leveraged to build up the patterns themselves or analyze and transform the programs that contain them.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL (*StriNg Oriented and symBOlic Language*) is a computer programming language developed between 1962 and 1967 at AT&T Bell Laboratories by David J.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 stands apart from most programming languages by having patterns as a first-class data type (*i.e.* a data type whose values can be manipulated in all ways permitted to any other data type in the programming language) and by providing operators for pattern concatenation and alternation.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Strings generated during execution can be treated as programs and executed.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL was quite widely taught in larger US universities in the late 1960s and early 1970s and was widely used in the 1970s and 1980s as a text manipulation language in the humanities.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] Since SNOBOL's creation, newer languages such as AWK and Perl have made string manipulation by means of regular expressions fashionable.
[src:miranda-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 patterns, however, subsume Backus–Naur form (BNF) grammars, which are equivalent to context-free grammars and more powerful than regular expressions.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] In computer science, **purely functional programming** usually designates a programming paradigm—a style of building the structure and elements of computer programs—that treats all computation as the evaluation of mathematical functions.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] This style handles state changes without losing the referential transparency of the program expressions.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programming consists of ensuring that functions, inside the functional paradigm, will only depend on their arguments, regardless of any global or local state.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] A pure functional subroutine only has visibility of changes of state represented by state variables included in its scope.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] The exact difference between pure and impure functional programming is a matter of controversy.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] Sabry's proposed definition of purity is that all common evaluation strategies (call-by-name, call-by-value, and call-by-need) produce the same result, ignoring strategies that error or diverge.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] A program is usually said to be functional when it uses some concepts of functional programming, such as first-class functions and higher-order functions.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] However, a first-class function need not be purely functional, as it may use techniques from the imperative paradigm, such as arrays or input/output methods that use mutable cells, which update their state as side effects.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] In fact, the earliest programming languages cited as being functional, IPL and Lisp, are both "impure" functional languages by Sabry's definition.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] Each evaluation strategy which ends on a purely functional program returns the same result.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] In particular, it ensures that the programmer does not have to consider in which order programs are evaluated, since eager evaluation will return the same result as lazy evaluation.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] However, it is still possible that an eager evaluation may not terminate while the lazy evaluation of the same program halts.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] An advantage of this is that lazy evaluation can be implemented much more easily; as all expressions will return the same result at any moment (regardless of program state), their evaluation can be delayed as much as necessary.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] In a purely functional language, the only dependencies between computations are data dependencies, and computations are deterministic.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, to program in parallel, the programmer need only specify the pieces that should be computed in parallel, and the runtime can handle all other details such as distributing tasks to processors, managing synchronization and communication, and collecting garbage in parallel.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] This style of programming avoids common issues such as race conditions and deadlocks, but has less control than an imperative language.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] To ensure a speedup, the granularity of tasks must be carefully chosen to be neither too big nor too small.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] In theory, it is possible to use runtime profiling and compile-time analysis to judge whether introducing parallelism will speed up the program, and thus automatically parallelize purely functional programs.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] In practice, this has not been terribly successful, and fully automatic parallelization is not practical.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are persistent.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] Persistency is required for functional programming; without it, the same computation could return different results.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] Functional programming may use persistent non-purely functional data structures, while those data structures may not be used in purely functional programs.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way than their imperative counterparts.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] For example, array with constant-time access and update is a basic component of most imperative languages and many imperative data-structures, such as hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by map or random access list, which admits purely functional implementation, but the access and update time is logarithmic.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, purely functional data structures can be used in languages which are non-functional, but they may not be the most efficient tool available, especially if persistency is not required.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] In general, conversion of an imperative program to a purely functional one also requires ensuring that the formerly-mutable structures are now explicitly returned from functions that update them, a program structure called store-passing style.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] A purely functional language is a language which only admits purely functional programming.
[src:miranda-language/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programs can however be written in languages which are not purely functional.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] In analytic philosophy and computer science, **referential transparency** and **referential opacity** are properties of linguistic constructions, and by extension of languages.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] A linguistic construction is called *referentially transparent* when for any expression built from it, replacing a subexpression with another one that denotes the same value does not change the value of the expression.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] Otherwise, it is called *referentially opaque*.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] Referential transparency, in programming languages, depends on semantic equivalences among denotations of expressions, or on contextual equivalence of expressions themselves.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] That is, referential transparency depends on the semantics of the language.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] So, both declarative languages and imperative languages can have referentially transparent positions, referentially opaque positions, or (usually) both, according to the semantics they are given.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] The importance of referentially transparent positions is that they allow the programmer and the compiler to reason about program behavior as a rewrite system at those positions.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] This can help in proving correctness, simplifying an algorithm, assisting in modifying code without breaking it, or optimizing code by means of memoization, common subexpression elimination, lazy evaluation, constant folding, or parallelization.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] There are three fundamental properties concerning substitutivity in formal languages: referential transparency, definiteness, and unfoldability.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] Let’s denote syntactic equivalence with ≡ and semantic equivalence with =.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] A *position* is defined by a sequence of natural numbers.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] The empty sequence is denoted by ε and the sequence constructor by ‘.’.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] In other words, a position is purely referential in an expression if and only if it is subject to the substitutivity of equals. ε is purely referential in all expressions.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] Otherwise Ω is *referentially opaque* in place i.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] An operator is *referentially transparent* is defined by it is referentially transparent in all places.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] A formal language is *referentially transparent* is defined by all its operators are referentially transparent.
