[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] So in the first position, the ‘_ refers to _’ operator restores the relation between an expression and the value that it denotes.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] The second position is also purely referential for the same substitutivity reason.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] A formal language is *definite* is defined by all the occurrences of a variable within its scope denote the same value.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] Indeed, the two occurrences of x denote the same value.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] A formal language is *unfoldable* is defined by all expressions are β-reducible.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] Referential transparency, definiteness, and unfoldability are independent.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] Definiteness implies unfoldability only for deterministic languages.
[src:miranda-language/referential-transparency] Non-deterministic languages cannot have definiteness and unfoldability at the same time.
